                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d779">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Commission/196</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese Assessor</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">League of Nations Manchuria Inquiry Commission</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="3" xml:id="d779fn3">Copy transmitted to the Chief of the Division of
                        Far Eastern Affairs by the Chinese Chargé in his note of April 28, 1932,
                        stating that the message was “relayed by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs,
                        Nanking, for the information of the State Department.”</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1932-04-28">undated</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>A message from the Chinese Assessor to the League of Nations Manchuria Inquiry
                    Commission in Mukden stated: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>The Chinese Assessor and his Staff have been completely isolated and
                            under strict surveillance by Japanese police agents in Mukden. All
                            Chinese were forbidden to approach or communicate with the Chinese
                            Delegation. Several Chinese were arrested for trying to call on the
                            Chinese Delegation members. Two arrests were eye-witnessed by <persName
                                corresp="#p_HE2">Edward Hunter</persName> of the International News
                            Service.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
            </div>
